{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608750/1958042201/0593.xml":{"full_text":"DAVID LAWRENCE\nPresidents and Recessions\nFronklin Roosevelt Called Executive\nMost Often Wrong in Forecasts\nPresident! and cabinet\nofficers are usually optimistic\nabout when the country Is to\nget out of a recession\u2014and\nsometimes they are right.\nThe President who wes\nmost often wrong in his fore\ncasts was the late Franklin\nD. Roosevelt. This la con\ntrary to the general Impres\nsion which has long prevailed,\nespecially as the remark that\n\u201cprosperity Is Just around the\ncorner\" was attributed to the\nadministration of President\nHoover.\nActually. Mr Hoover never\nsaid anything of the sort. In\ntheir political speeches, the\nDemocrats accused him of\noveroptimism and kept re\npeating the phrase which he\nnever uttered. What he did\nsay resembles closely what\nPresident Roosevelt later said\nand what has been heard\nquite recently from present\nday speakers. Mr. Hoover\nsaid In May. 1930:\n\"I am convinced we now\nhave passed the worst and\nwith continued unity of ef\nfort we shall rapidly recover\nThere Is one certainty In the\nfuture of a people of the re\nsource s, Intelligence, and\ncharacter of the people of\nthe United States\u2014that is.\nprosperity.\u201d\nBy April. 1931, when un\nemployment had risen. Mr.\nHoover again qualified his\nprediction as he said: \u201cIf.\nby the grace of God, we have\npassed the worst of this\nstorm, the future months\nwill be easy. If we shall be\ncalled upon to endure more\nof this period, we must gird\nourselves for even greater\neffort.\"\nBut when President Roose\nDORIS FLEESON\nPre-election Power for Nixon?\nVice President Expected to Move Into\nWhite House Before '6O Conventions\nThere Is not a single Demo\ncratic politician who has not\nwritten in his future book\nthese two predictions:\n1. Vice President Richard\nM. Nixon will take power at\nthe White House sometime\nprior to the 1960 presidential\nnominating conventions so\nthat he may enjoy the im\nmense advantages of incum\nbency well before he enters\nthe campaign itself.\n2. He will initiate Instantly\na great burst of activity on\ncivil rights designed to wipe\nout the Eisenhower record of\ndawdling on that issue.\nThe question of the Presi\ndent's health enters Into cal\nculations only as It will fur\nnish the obvious excuse for\nmoving up Mr. Nixon. Dem\nocrats are satisfied that the\nsame Instinct for self-pres\nervation which led Republi\ncans to draft Mr. Eisenhower\nin 1956. despite his health\nproblems, will operate again\nto put Irresistible pressures\non the President to make way\nfor the Vice President.\nBy his own actions Mr.\nNixon has made it plain he\nplans to win the election\nthrough his appeal to the\nminorities of the pivotal\nBtates in the industrial\nNorth and East, plus Califor\nnia. What is remarkable is\nthat, knowing this, the Dem\nDOROTHY THOMPSON\nCliburn Conquered Russian Bear\nPresident Chided for Belated Note\nOs Congratulations to Young Pianist\nThe President, via the\nAmerican ambassador to\nMoscow, has conveyed his\ncongratulations to young Van\nCliburn. and invited him to\nvisit the White House upon\nhis return to the United\nStates.\nThe action seems to this\ncolumnist a little belated.\nWe would have anticipated\nthat the young Texan who\nwalked off with the coveted\ngold medal in a musical com\npetition. that in Russia in\nduces the excitement of the\nworld aeries here, would have\nInstantly received a con\ngratulatory cable from Presi\ndent Eisenhower, not only for\nhis great satisfaction and\nhappiness, but to open and\nread to his international col\nleagues. The youth, who.\nembraced by Khrushchev,\nsaid he was \u201ca sweet man.\"\nwould certainly have re\nsponded as warmly and spon\ntaneously to such an Immedi\nate communication. But bet\nter late than never.\nVan Cliburn has appeared\nwith the New York Philhar\nmonic and many others since\nhe won the Leventrltt award\nIn 1954. From what his ad\nmirers <and even his critics)\nsay. It is easy to understand\nwhy he received the Immense\novation that he did in Mos\ncow. He has an Immensely\nmoving talent, full of poetry\nand romantic feeling, a tal\nent of an almost vanished\nsort, not quite acceptable to\nmodem musical snobs, who\nin music as In other arts,\ndismiss feeling as somehow\n\u2022\u2022corny.\"\nThat he Is, at 23. splendidly\nequipped technically, as the\nresult of enormous musical\ndedication and work, must\nbe taken for granted. One\ndoes not win Moscow's gold\nmedal without It.\nBut one does not move an\naudience to wild ovations by\ntechnique alone. That Is\ndone by communication. And.\n1 find it significant that ths^\nvelt took office he became\ncontinuously optimistic Thus\non January 4. 1934. In his\nannual message to Congress,\nhe said: \"Now that we are\ndefinitely In the process of\nrecovery.\"\nBut In 1934 the number of\nunemployed had Jumped\nfrom 11,586.000 In November\n1933. during the Hoover ad\nministration. to 13,282.000\nYet during that same year\n\u2014on September 6. 1934\u2014Mr.\nRoosevelt remained optimis\ntic when he said: \u201cIt is a\nsource of great satisfaction\nthat at this moment condi\ntions are such as to oiler\nfurther substantial and wide\nspread recovery.\"\nThere was. indeed, a 10\nper cent Improvement re\ncorded In January. 1935. over\nthe figures of January. 1934.\nIt was a drop of 1,224 000.\nand Mr. Roosevelt said on\nApril 28. 1935:\n\"Never since my inaugura\ntion In March. 1933, have I\nfelt so unmistakably the at\nmosphere of recovery.\nFear is vanishing and con\nfidence is growing on ebery\nside, faith Is being renewed.\"\nThen on October 23. 1935,\nMr. Roosevelt said: \u201cYes, we\nare on our wav back.\nWe are coming back more\nsoundly than ever before, be\ncause we are planning it that\nway. Don't let anybody tell\nyou differently.\"\nBut these statements proved\nto be too optimistic and by\nJanuary. 1936. unemployment\nactually increased by 600.000\nover January. 1935. All dur\ning 1936, however, Mr. Roose\nvelt remained optimistic, and\non September 4. 1936, he\nsaid flatly, \"Prosperity Is\nocratic Congress Is a silent\npartner In the White House's\napathy on civil rights.\nThe much-touted Eisen\nhower Civil Rights Commis\nsion. created by law eight\nmonths aeo. is still not func\ntioning. The President did\nnot name a staff director un\ntil February 20: since then\nSoutherners in Congress have\nstalled his confirmation and\ncommission appropriations\u2014\namid thunders of silence from\nthe White House and Demo\ncratic leaders.\nThe rioters at Little Rock\nlast fall, who drew the world's\nshocked attention to that\nSouthern capital, are happily\ngoing about their segrega\ntionist business. Not a single\none has been convicted, much\nless gone to jail. They were\narrested for contempt of a\nFederal court but turned over\nto State courts for trial where\nthey were turned loose with\nwhat almost amounted to\ngood conduct medals.\nLast week Attorney Gen\neral William Rogers. Mr.\nNixon's most intimate friend,\nlaid the groundwork for\nblaming Democrats for this\nOutcome.\nUr was warned by Editor\nHarry Ashmore that the Lit\ntle Rock segregationists were\ntwo most effective ambassa\ndors yet sent abroad from\nthis country are both musi\ncians with an extraordinary\ncommunicative power\u2014Miss\nMarlon Anderson and now\nVan Cliburn.\n1 also find it significant\nthat, although neither has\nvery intimate connections\nwith organized religions, both\nare profoundly religious.\nAn intimate friend of Mr.\nCliburn tells me that on the\nSunday he was to appear for\nthe first time with the Phila\ndelphia Orchestra he In\nquired anxiously, \u201cShall I\nstay home and practice or\ngo to church?\" He decided\non church.\nThere Is a lovingness about\nthe really, though inconspic\nuously, religious that com\nmunicates.\n\"I\u2019m really a ham.\" young\nCliburn said to another\nfriend. \u201cWhen I walk out on\nthe stage I Just love every\nbody.\" So. of course, for such\nis a law of human nature, he\nis loved in return. Such peo\nple never make false moves,\nthough none of them is cal\nculated. They say the right\nthings, do the right things,\nand disarm everybody\u2014ex\ncept possibly musical critics.\nOn stage or off they are al\nways on the right channel.\nYoung Mr. Cliburn ap\nproached the bear as An\ndrocles approaches the lion.\nIn one of Bernard Shaw\u2019s\nmost delightful plays. And.\nlike the lion, the bear kissed\nhim. He went to the sum\nmit and played Tchaikovsky,\nand the summit delightedly\ngave him a gold medal. It\nwas a complete conquest to\neverybody's satisfaction.\nThe whole story is delight\nful. Van Cliburn is a grass\nroots native American from\nTexas associated with tall\nmen (which he is), noble\ncowboys and ttadmen, both\nequally quick on the trigger.\nTexans are uniformly repre\nsented <on TV at least) as\ncontinually shooting each\ncoming back.\" He went fur\nther and said In October that\n\"We a rev around the comer.\"\nUnemployment had gone\ndown during the year and\nstood In January, 1937. at\n10.002.000. Then. In 1938.\nIt went up again to 10,936.-\n000. In fact. In 1939 before\nWorld War U came and\nbegan to furnish war orders,\nthe total unemployed had\nreached 11.389.000, which was\nJust about the same as It\nwas at the time of FDR's\nelection in November, 1932.\nSo no progress, statistically\nspeaking, had been made in\nseven years.\nIn the recession that began\nIn 1949, President Truman\nalso made various statements\nof an optimistic nature, but\nhere, too, the recession was\nended by the outbreak of a\nwar\u2014ln Korea.\nSo optimism seems to come\nnaturally to the men at the\nhead of the Government,\nand perhaps this happens\nbecause in critical times an\nattitude of pessimism can\nItself generate more fear and\nmore hesitation In business\nand consequently produce\nmore layoffs of workers.\nNo man who Is President\ncan fall to look at things\nfrom the long view\u2014he feels\nconfident In the ultimate re\ncovery of the country from\nperiods of recession. What\never criticism Is made, there\nfore, of the statements Issued\nby a President should take\nInto account the confidence\nhe feels at the moment as\nthe figures come In to show\nImprovement, too President\nwould deliberately cover up\nthe facts, but. being con\nvinced of the soundness of\nthe Nation's economy In the\nlong run. he has a natural\ntendency to \u201caccentuate the\npositive.\"\n(Seproduction Rishu ae\u00bbrr\u00bbrS>\ndally growing bolder, bullying\nthe school board and boy\ncotting all persons and en\nterprises deemed unfriendly.\nMr. Rogers said he was help\nless. that Congress had dis\ncarded that provision of last\nyear's legislation whiclf would\nhave enabled him to act.\nThe federalized National\nGuard is still on duty at Lit\ntle Rock. It is denied official\nly but widely understood in\nthat city that they have or\nders never to arrest anyone\nbut simply to take any dis\nturber of the peace to the\nschool principal\u2014a prescrip\ntion for inaction.\nThe eyes of the world will\nturn again to Little Rock\nJuly 29 when the State ac\ncepts or rejects Gov. Orval\nFaubus in the Democratic\nprimary, a victory which is\ntantamount to election. By\ndefying the Federal power\nlast fall. Gov. Faubus became\nthe segregationists' hero; he\nis counting on them to break\nthe re-election Jinx on the\nState's Governors.\nA law-and-order candidate\nis opposing him\u2014Judge Lee\nWard of the chancery court.\nJudge Ward is a former State\ncommander of the American\nLegion who opposes integra\ntion but is calling for a rule\nof law. The primary closes\nthis month; so far, only Gov.\nFaubus and Judge Ward\nhave entered It.\nother when not spending oil\nmoney like the late Roman\nemperors.\nIf Van Cliburn's country\nwere to turn up a musician,\none would expect an Elvis\nPresley, or a rock 'n' roller.\nWith Van Cliburn, neither\noil-rich, trigger-happy, nor\nholy or, unholy roller, one\nmust abandon such generali\n'zations.\nThe Russians are a highly\nresponsive audience who can\nfreeze as well as thaw. In\nRussia my impression was\nthat they are less conform\nist in this small area of free\ndom than we. They don\u2019t\nwait to read what the critic*\nsay to learn whether they\nreally ought to like or dis\nlike a show.\nIn the case of the young\nTexan, critics and audience\nagreed, but the audience ex\npressed Itself first.\nYoung Republicans\nFight for Office\nOpposing candidates for of\nfices in the District Young Re\npublicans Club campaigned\nvigorously among 250 of their\nfellow members last night at a\nconvention in the sutler Hotel.\nHeading the two slates were\npresidential candidates Don\nTubirdy. a field assistant with\nthe G.O.P. Congressional Cam\npaign Committee, and Biehl I.\ni Bundy i Clarke, an official with\nthe United States Chamber of\nCommerce.\nElection of club officers will\ntake place next Monday from\n5:30 to 9 p.m. In the hotel.\nButler to Speak\nOn Foreign Aid\nSenator Butler. Republican\nof Maryland, will speak on\n\u201cThe New Dimension of For\neign Aid\" at a public meeting\nat 8 p.m. Thursday at Bethea\nda-Chevy Chase High Bchool.\nThe meeting Is sponsored by\n|the Montgomery County Con-\nAtvative Club.\nLOUIE \u2014l*\nL__!;\nPOTOMAC FEVER\nFLCTCHCR KNEBCL\nWomen Democrats convene in Washington. Only a\nwoman could denounce the Eisenhower team for concealing\nvital information\u2014while attired In a sack dress.\n\nDefense Boss McElroy says we can \u201cbury\" Khrushchev\nbefore he buries us Tombstone marker: \"Here lie the\nremains of Sam and Ivan. Since both were right, neither\none's survivin\u2019.\"\n\nChairman Butler says the 1960 Democratic candidate will\nbe more liberal. Anything else you can tell us about him.\naside from his expensive tastes?\n\nHarry Truman apologizes for denying an Interview by\nArthur Krock. It's a wise man who knows when he's been\nrun over by a printing press\n\nEconomists\u2019 recession Jargon: \u201cIncreased labor force\u201d\u2014\nMarching the young man out to the back yard and hand\ncuffing him to the lawn mower.\n\nRussian and American veterans of the 1945 Elbe River\nmeeting hold a reunion. Russian: \u201cCommunism is timeless.\"\nAmerican: \u201cIn that case, how about giving me back my\nwrist watch?\"\n\nNew York's Oov. Harrtman urges lower taxes and higher\nspending. Democrats figure the way out of this thing is to\nboom the glass industry\u2014and do everything with mirrors.\nP Jr? F\\\njy KEEP UP THE COOP WORK! I\nAGAIN AND AGAIN, industrial newcomers its workers. 11 helps management keep production\n\u00ab4jgfl to the Southland tell us how pleased they cost per unit down, so that the finished product \u2019lifr\npHl' are with their first manufacturing plant in the can be priced to sell in today\u2019s highly competitive wKF-.U\nWm.WM South. There are many reasons for this. But right markets. And this, in turn, makes >ohs for workers. p J\nMM B up on top of the list is the fact that they\u2019ve found A MmW\\\nfflJ x A good supply of good workers has always been BOrJ\nJmmm the men and women in industry here to be willing, 0 Ti\noneoftheSouthlandsgreatestdrawmgcards.lt\nJjt Jfi| g a j uU da y g work j or a da y s brings new, job-providing manufacturing plants J\nf /U| In times of lessened business activity everywhere, get here. Now in particular it benefits everyone\nthis willingness to work is more important than in the Southland to \u201ckeep up the good work\u201d\never before, both for Southland industry and for and keep it that way! V _\n\nWE WANT YOUR FREIGHT IN '5Bl |H|\nTo shippers and receivers of freight, the railroad that \u201cServes SOUTH I* R K| B|F,\nthe South\u201d now offers the largest, most efficient, most modem I IKIVI w\nMsfsm plant and equipment in its 127-year history. As never before, _ _ ______ __ _\nwe are eager to serve and geared to GO. Let our low-rate, all- RAI LV\\fAl Si STEM\ni weather volume transportation service help you do a better job\n-for your shipping dollar. This year, ship via Southern and see! Washington, d c. Jf'\nBp*'\"\nbrP'H pbM|\nCONSTANTINE BROWN\nKhrushchev Wooing Franco\nRed Premier Reported Angling for Bid\nTo Visit Spanish Generalissimo\nThe Kremlin Is working\novertime to Isolate America\nfrom her associates, especial\nly those on whose soil we have\nImportant Interests.\nRecent Information from\nhighly reliable sources la that\nPremier Khrushchev is woo\ning\u2014from a distance\u2014Oen\nerallsalmo Francisco Franco\nHe has Intimated through\ndiplomatic channels In Paris\nand London that he would\nlike very much to visit Mad\nrid and make the acquaint\nance of that \u201cvaliant head of\ngovernment who has been\nable to pilot so successfully\nthe destinies of his people\nover the last two decades of\nImmeasurable difficulties.\"\nAccording to the same\nsources. Khrushchev would\nbe willing to settle the irk\nsome dispute over the nearly\ntl billion In gold sent to the\nUSSR by the Loyalist gov\nernment for safekeeping dur\ning the civil war. This gold\nwas stolen by the Soviet gov\nernment under the excuse\nthat It had been used for\nsupplying the Loyalist armies\nGen. Franco appears to be\nwary of Russians bearing\ngifts, since he knows that the\nprice of Moscow's \u201cfriend\nship\u201d Is to cancel the agree\nments for American air and\nnaval bases In Spain. The\nRussian approaches are not\nbeing given publicity In\nSpain, where economic con\nditions due to the speeded\nup standard of living are\ncausing serious difficulties.\nAnd if American military and\neconomic aid were curtailed\nas seems possible the\nMadrid government is wor\nried lest there may be a\nserious outcry especially in\nthe restless Industrial areas\nfor a change In attitude to\nward the Boviet Union. The\npro-Soviet sympathizers al\nready are exploiting the\ncloseness of our main air\nTHE EVENING BTAR. Washington, D. C.\nTiigsi>4T, Avan, as. Teas\nbases to densely populated\nareas such as Madrid, itself.\nIt takes all the tact and\nprestige of the generalissimo\nto counter the Soviet propa\nganda that has become so\nsuddenly concerned over\nM\u2019ain's well-being Spain is\nthese days a dictatorship In\nname only. It Is moving fast\ntoward a democracy in which\nthe government may soon be\ndirected by the voice of the\npeople. Khrushchev knows\nthis. Hence, his desire to visit\n(Spain.\nThe Soviet propagandists\nplay up skillfully the specter\nof America's recession and\neventual inability to continue\nsupport of her friends. They\nuse scary speeches and state\nments by American political\nand economic leaders to\nbolster their words. With\nequal skill the alleged \u201cIn\ncrease\u201d of Soviet economic\npotential announced by\nKhrushchev is being utilized.\nRecently he predicted that\nthe Soviet Union will quickly\noutdistance the United\nBtales' industrial and agri\ncultural output. But the fore\nmost argument that Spain\nmay become a target of So\nviet nuclear weapons Is be\ning stressed by the clandes\ntine Spanish radio estab\nlished in France close to the\nborder.\nDiplomatic observers cog\nnizant of this new \u201cpassion\"\nof Khrushchev for our Span\nish friends fear that the new\nbrewing conflict between\nSpain and Morocco may give\nhim an improved chance to\nexploit his efforts to dis\njoint the expensively put to\ngether American alliance. We\nare in a fix In &gard to\nNorth Africa. Our policy\u2014\nas far as can be gathered\nby Washington observers\u2014\nIs to sit on two separate\nchairs. We are wooing the\nArabs and at the same time\nwant to keep the friendship\nof the Spaniards and ths\nFrench who have deep In\nterests In North Africa.\nThe Russians are openly\ncommitted to Arab nation\nalism. But they can make\ndeals with France or Spain\nwhenever they like without\nappearing to change their\npolicies. All they need to do\nin the event, for Instance,\nthat they want to reach an\nagreement with a French\ngovernment willing to give\nup membership In the NATO\nIs to cut off the supplies of\narms and military techni\ncians they have been rush\ning to North Africa for the\nlast few years.\nThe Spanish government\nhas handled the North Afri\ncan situation Intelligently. It\nmade an agreement with the\nMoroccan government on Its\nown volition and In a spirit\nof friendship and reciprocal\nrespect. The new conflict Is\nsaid to have been forced by\nthe Istiqlal (the ultra-nation\nalist party of Morocco* which\nhas had and continues to\nhave direct ties with Moscow.\nThe policy of the Istiqlal\nseems to be that \"If anybody\ngives you his hand ask for\nthe whole arm.\u201d They want\ncomplete control over the\nmineral-rich areas 111 the\nsouthern desert to which the\nkingdom of Morocco has no\nclaim.\nThe Madrid government Is\nconcerned over the situation\nbut does not expect any ef\nfective help from Washing\nton. Should the situation\nworsen it would be happy\nif we Just kept out of It. But\nthe expectations are that be\ncause of our air bases In Mo\nrocco and our fear that we\nmight be tagged once more\nby the Communists as Im\nperialists, there might be un\nofficial notes to Madrid ad\nvising \u201ctolerance.\" Khru\nshchev. say those who urge\nhis being received In Madrid,\nhas no such handicap.\nA-13","height":"29446","width":"18445"}}
